Response Rates Over Time

State and County Self-Response Rates Over Time

  • The USCB started publishing self-response rate data on 03/20/2020.

  • While the state response rate is consistently about 4-5 percentage points above the county rate, both state and county rates have steadily increased throughout the self-response period.

  • Over the past month, however, self-response rates have plateaued. The state self-response rate increased by only 0.9 percentage points over the last two weeks (06/15 to 07/01), and the county rate increased by only 0.6 percentage points.

  • The final self-response rate for California in 2010 was 68.2%, and the final 2010 rate for Los Angeles County was 69%.

  • Both CA and LA County have substantial ground to cover before meeting their respective 2010 self-response rates, but we continue to see steady increases in self-response despite challenges, including those related to COVID-19 stay-at-home orders.

Regional Self-Response Rates Over Time

  • In LA County, the majority of hard-to-count census tracts have a lower response rate than the state rate and the county rate. However, we see a continuous creep upward in self-response rate, even in the regions with the largest concentration of HTC tracts.

  • The hard work of CBOs doing Census outreach is reflected in the continuous, incremental increase in self-response rates.

  • Self-response rates in all regions increased by less than 1 percentage point over the last two weeks (from 06/15 to 07/01).

  • South LA had the largest percentage point increase of 0.7 percentage points, which increased its response rate by 1.4%. However, South LA has the greatest concentration of HTC tracts and started off at a lower response rate. South LA still has a self-response rate below 50% and remains an urgent outreach priority.

  • South LA, Central LA, and Northeast/Eastside/East LA are the lowest responding regions and we should focus our attention, efforts and resources on these hard-to-count regions

  • Central LA has become the lowest-responding region in the county, right behind South LA.

Current Regional Self-Response Rates vs. 2010 Regional Rates

  • All regions are still lagging behind their final 2010 self-response rates, although some regions–those with fewer HTC tracts–are closer than others.

  • Central and South LA are about 15% behind their final 2010 self-response rates. Northeast-Eastside-East LA is nearly 20% behind its previous rate.

Response Rate by Primary HTC Characteristic

All Census Tracts

  • California Complete Count identifies the top hard-to-count (HTC) characteristic in each census tract.

  • Looking at the top HTC characteristics in all census tracts, the most common top HTC characteristic is multi-unit structures, followed by foreign born population and crowded units.

  • In census tracts where the top HTC characteristic is Households without broadband subscription, we see about 51.7% of households have responded so far. This is the current HTC group with the lowest response rate.

  • Urgent outreach priority:

    • Based on lowest response rates, census tracts where the top HTC characteristic is: Households without broadband subscription, households Below 150 percent of poverty level and Renter-occupied units are the most urgent outreach priority.

    • Based on highest number of uncounted households, census tracts where the top HTC characteristic is: Multi-unit structures, Crowded units, and Foreign-born population.

Countywide: Response Rate in Communities by Demographic

  • Data Note: We do not have data on who is responding to the Census, we only know the number of households that have responded in each tract.

  • For these plots, we identified the census tracts with a high share (highest quintile) of each demographic group. For example, in 20% of census tracts in LA County the tract population is 11.2% Black or higher. These tracts make up the top quintile of census tracts for the Black population. The quintile thresholds that define ‘top quintile’ tracts for other demographic groups are shown below.

Top Quintile Thresholds

  • Census tracts where the AIAN population is greater than 1.1%
  • Census tracts where the Asian population is greater than 21.9%
  • Census tracts where the Black population is greater than 11.2%
  • Census tracts where the Latinx population is greater than 77.8%
  • Census tracts where the NHPI population is greater than 0.3%
  • Census tracts where the Other/Two or More population is greater than 39.3%
  • Census tracts where the White non-Latinx population is greater than 54.3%
  • Census tracts where the foreign born population is greater than 45.5%
  • Census tracts where the limited English proficient (LEP) population is greater than 37.3%

  • The top 20% of census tracts for % Latinx population have a combined response rate of 53.0%. This is the lowest combined self-response rate in the county.

  • The top 20% of census tracts for % Black population have a combined response rate of 54.7%.

  • Communities with large Latinx and Black populations have a greater concentration of hard-to-count tracts, which is reflected in these response rate estimates.

  • In top 20% of census tracts for the Foreign Born population, the combined self-response rate is estimated to be 56.3%.

  • In the top 20% of census tracts for the Language other than English population, the combined self-response rate is 53.0%.

Regions: Response Rate in Communities by Demographic

  • Data Note: We do not have data on who is responding to the Census, we only know the number of households that have responded in each tract.

  • For these plots, we identified the census tracts with a high share (top 20%) of each demographic group. For example, in 20% of census tracts in LA County the Black population makes up 11.2% or higher of the total population. This is the top quintile of census tracts for the Black population. The response rates for all the census tracts in the top quintile for the Black population within each region are shown below.

  • The concentration of HTC census tracts varies greatly across the county. Some regions have more than 150 HTC tracts, some regions have less than 20. Self-response rate varies widely across the county as well. South LA, Central LA and Northeast/Eastside LA are currently the lowest-responding regions, and also have the greatest concentration of hard-to-count census tracts.

  • HTC characterstics, such as access to internet, vary across the county.

By Race/Ethnicity and Region

  • Response rates in top-quintile census tracts by demographic group also varies by region. Although some regions have higher response rates–such as San Gabriel Valley West–it is likely that not all demographic groups are responding equally.

  • For example, in San Gabriel Valley West, top quintile tracts for White non-Latinx people have a response rate of 73.5%, which is 11.7 percentage points higher than top quintile tracts for Black people in the region, and 19.4 percentage points higher than top quintile tracts for Latinx people in the region.

  • Urgent outreach target: All people living in South LA, Central LA and NELA. Antelope Valley is also falling behind. Additional outreach is needed for Black and Latinx Angelenos in all regions.

By Demographic and Region

  • Top quintile tracts for people who don’t speak English well have a slightly lower response rate than top quintile tracts for foreign born people, however, all people in South, CEntral and NELA need additional outreach.

  • Priority outreach target: People who were born outside of the US living in South LA, Central and NELA.

  • Priority outreach target: People who don’t speak English well living in South LA, South Bay East, Central LA, NELA, Pomona Valley and Long Beach.

Outreach Priorities

Hard-to-count communities and regions with low response rates.

We recommend outreach time and resources be devoted to boosting response rates in these priority communities.

Priority Communities by Demographics

Priority communities are determined by calculating the combined self-response rate for census tracts that are in the top quintile for various demographics (for example, the top 20% of limited English proficient census tracts). Census tracts where more than half of the population lives in group quarters have been excluded.

  • Priority communities for targeting outreach to limited English proficient speakers & people born outside of the US are located in Central and South LA.

  • These communities have low self-response rates in tracts where the share of LEP and foreign born populations are in the highest quintile.

  • Central-Alameda, Historic South-Central and Pico-Union are priority communities for both people who don’t speak English well and for people who were born outside the US.

Priority communities by race/ethnicity

Many priority communities for targeting outreach to various demographic groups are located in South LA and Central LA, as these regions have the lowest overall self-response rates.

  1. Central-Alameda and Historic South-Central in South LA are priority communities for Latinx and American Indian/Alaskan Native (AIAN) people living in low-responding tracts.

  2. Downtown LA is a priority community for Black, Asian and Native Hawaiian/Pacific Islander (NHPI) populations living in low-responding tracts.

  3. Pico-Union is a priority community for Asian, Latinx and American Indian/Alaskan Native (AIAN) people living in low-responding tracts.

  4. Westlake is a priority community for Latinx and NHPI populations.

About We Count LA

Advancement Project California partnered with the California Community Foundation to convene the We Count LA Census Table. Under one brand and one mission, to secure a fair and accurate count of all Angelenos, the We Count LA Census Table brings together community-based organizations and other census stakeholders (philanthropy, state/local government, business) to share resources and coordinate planned activities across the region and particularly in high-need census tracts.

 

Published by Advancement Project California
